<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10955&amp;p=124861#p124861"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Games that used the window for special effects?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10955&amp;p=124861#p124861"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Grumskiz wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=skzu3VL7_38<br /><br />Chikyuu Kaihou Gun I think is a very interesting example in that it actually uses two background layers scrolling at different speeds.<br />The effect really shows in later levels I think.<br /></div>That game is using a bunch of interesting tricks, but as far as I can see nothing that is using the window, from a quick look at that video.<br />6:16 Scrolling &quot;behind&quot; the background by writing new tile data for some tiles.<br />8:33 Switching between between two BG maps every frame, and then lets the LCD lag take care of the frame blending.<br />11:32 This effect is done by changing the SCX and SCY coordinates and probably map source mid-frame. This effect actually CAN'T be done by the window because of its limitations. (The drawing must always start relative to position 0,0 of the selected map.)<br />23:38 This boss <em>might</em> be done using the window, but it could also probably be done with the background+sprites. The advantage of doing it that way is that you get hardware mirroring for free.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4548">nitro2k01</a> — Sun Feb 02, 2014 7:28 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
